article.description: Lisa Harrison scored 14 points and made the go-ahead basket as the Phoenix Mercury handed the Minnesota Lynx their fourth consecutive defeat, 70-61.
article.headline: Mercury's balanced scoring keeps Lynx in tailspin
article.linkText: Harrison leads Mercury past slumping Lynx
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Once Lisa Harrison got back on the court, the
Phoenix Mercury got back in the game.

	   Harrison scored 14 points while Adriana Moises and rookie
Susanna Bonfiglio each added 11 as Phoenix rallied to beat the
Minnesota Lynx 70-61 Sunday night.

	   Adrain Williams finished with nine rebounds for Phoenix (6-3),
which won for just the second time in four games.

	   Harrison was taken out of the game in the first half by Mercury
coach Cynthia Cooper.

	   "I had some issues with her on the court, but the No. 1 thing
is we're trying to win,'' said Cooper, who declined to discuss why
she was upset with Harrison. "I put her back in when I felt like
it and she played like she's paid to play.''

	   Harrison also refused to talk about why Cooper was mad at her.

	   "That's between me and the coach,'' she said.

	   Minnesota (4-7) lost its fourth in a row despite rookie Tamika
Williams' 19 points and 12 rebounds, including a franchise-record
10 offensive boards.

	   Williams also tied a WNBA record with eight offensive rebounds
in one half and was one shy of the league mark for offensive boards
in one game.

	   Moises, who scored all of her points off the bench in 20
minutes, helped the Mercury erase a 33-32 halftime deficit.

	   Katie Smith, the league's defending scoring champion who's
averaging 18.3 points this season, scored just 10 against Phoenix
on 2-for-10 shooting from the field.

	   The game saw six ties and 12 lead changes until the Mercury took
control by opening the second half with a 21-8 run.

	   Phoenix made 14 of its 16 foul shots in the second half while
Minnesota was 14-for-26 in the game from free throw line.

	   Bonfiglio made five of her eight shots from the field in her first
career start.

	   "I was very nervous,'' she said. "I can score and the team
needed a shooter on the floor. I tried to provide that for us.''
